One last dish: US restaurateur drives six hours to fulfil dying woman’s wish

Heather Bowers was suffering from cancer and wanted to eat her favorite meal from Mama Kwans – Kevin Cherry made it happen

Ramon Antonio Vargas
Tue 2 Apr 2024 06.00 EDTLast modified on Tue 2 Apr 2024 11.13 EDT

Kevin Cherry didn’t want recognition for dropping everything he was doing and driving a half-dozen hours across state lines to fulfil a person’s dying wish.

But he got it anyway after loved ones of a West Virginia woman who received one last act of kindness in her final hours publicly expressed their eternal gratitude to Cherry, a North Carolina restaurant owner whose benevolence has vaulted him to internet virality.

As recounted on Friday in a WAVY news report shared widely in corners of the internet dedicated to finding uplifting news stories, Cherry’s Mama Kwans Tiki Bar & Grill got a phone call in late February from the friend of a cancer-stricken woman on her deathbed.

The caller, Mary Simmons, made clear that her friend Heather Bowers, a registered nurse, was preparing to leave behind her children and husband at age 47. And as she entered her final hours Bowers wanted – one last time – to eat her favorite meal: a pork plate from Mama Kwans, the restaurant her family most preferred when on vacation.

Simmons told WAVY that she thought it would be a long shot for Mama Kwans to be able to deliver a meal in time. The restaurant in the Outer Banks community of far east North Carolina was about six hours away from where Simmons was at Bowers’ side.

But then Simmons said she got a call back from Mama Kwans. The restaurant said its owner had packed up Bowers’ meal. “He’s in the car and he’s on his way there,” Simmons recalled being told. “He’s on his way.”

Cherry told WAVY that the drive to Bowers was emotionally grueling and it was showing on his face. “About halfway up, I had to turn the radio off and had to talk to myself saying, ‘You can’t walk in here like this. You’ve got to walk in with a little bit of sunshine from the Outer Banks.’”

He arrived in time for Bowers to enjoy the Mama Kwans pork plate she had on her mind in her waning moments. She died the next night.

A GoFundMe page set up to benefit Bowers’ family said she had spent the last few years of her life undergoing treatment for her illness, even traveling to Houston’s renowned MD Anderson cancer center. Her treatment included chemotherapy that took a devastating toll on her body, Simmons said to WAVY.

“What she went through in three and a half years would’ve brought down the strongest man,” Simmons remarked.

That is why Cherry’s delivery of the pork plate prepared by his staff at Mama Kwans was a vital reminder to Bowers and her supporters that there was still good in a world where multiple wars are raging simultaneously. And they hoped somehow such kindness could spread, according to Simmons.

“Simply put, he made one of her last wishes come true,” Simmons said of Cherry in a Facebook post. “This is something he didn’t want recognition for – however, kindness at this level deserves it.

“I speak for the whole Bowers family when I say thank you and God bless your amazing heart.”

Cherry told WAVY that he planned to donate $1,000 to the hospice which cared for Bowers at the end of her life. And he also told the station he believed anyone given the chance that he had would have done the same for Bowers.

One of the first comments to Simmons’ post about Cherry summarized the typical reaction to the way the restaurateur stepped up for Bowers.

“This whole thing almost leaves me speechless,” the comment said. “There really are good people out there.”

Another reply added: “Kevin, you will have a special place in heaven.”
